Package: mediawiki-dom-snapshot
Architecture: all
Depends: ${misc:Depends},
 python3,
 python3-bs4,
 python3-lxml,
 python3-pil,
 python3-imagehash,
 python3-playwright
Recommends: chromium
Description: Headless DOM + asset + screenshot snapshotter for MediaWiki regression testing
 Drives a headless Chromium against a running MediaWiki instance via
 Playwright, captures per page the post-JS DOM, a viewport screenshot,
 and every external asset body indexed by sha256, then offers a
 three-axis diff (HTML text, asset content, screenshot pixel +
 perceptual-hash distance) so a refactor can be proven not to have
 changed anything visually or behaviourally.
 .
 Use case: detect HTML/CSS/JS/image changes introduced by MediaWiki
 core / extension upgrades or by site-CSS refactors. Capture a
 baseline before the change, run again after, run the diff.
 .
 Ships the page list under /etc/mediawiki-dom-snapshot/pages.conf. The
 baseline corpus and capture output are large, regenerable runtime data
 kept in the operator's private cache, not in the package.

Package: sdwdate-gui-tests
Architecture: all
Depends: ${misc:Depends},
 python3,
 python3-pyqt5,
 sdwdate-gui
Suggests: xvfb,
 stalonetray,
 xdotool,
 x11-utils,
 weston,
 qtwayland5,
 dbus,
 python3-dbus,
 python3-gi,
 python3-coverage
Description: Regression tests and fuzzer for the sdwdate-gui applet
 Headless test suite for sdwdate-gui-server. Drives the real
 SdwdateTrayIcon and SdwdateGuiClient classes under the Qt offscreen
 platform plugin, so most of it needs neither an X server, a system
 tray, nor a live qrexec connection.
 .
 Unit coverage ('sdwdate-gui-tests' command): the client de-duplication
 invariant that keeps a Qubes VM from being listed more than once in the
 tray menu when it reconnects (Qubes authenticated-qrexec-name and
 non-Qubes self-reported-name branches), tray menu activation (left- and
 right-click open the menu; the Wayland opt-out), and wire-protocol
 regressions (a fragmented message must not hang the parser, a newline in
 a status message must not get the client kicked), and tray-deferral
 invariants (the tray icon waits for a system tray host so Qt binds
 StatusNotifier rather than the XEmbed fallback, while the IPC socket comes
 up immediately and pre-tray clients are buffered and replayed).
 .
 Fuzzer ('sdwdate-gui-tests-fuzz' command): a simulator that drives the
 server over a real local socket with a directed corpus plus random and
 mutated byte streams and random client-lifecycle sequences, for both the
 Qubes and non-Qubes paths. It checks for hangs, crashes, duplicate
 names, failed registration / de-registration, and stuck menus, and (with
 python3-coverage) reports line coverage of the server. The RNG seed is
 printed so any finding is reproducible.
 .
 Integration coverage ('sdwdate-gui-tests-integration' command): the same
 tray menu driven end to end on a real display -- a headless Xvfb with an
 XEmbed systray host for genuine left- and right-click delivery, a
 headless Wayland compositor for the Wayland opt-out, and a late-started
 StatusNotifierWatcher on a private session bus that guards against the
 tray-icon startup race (deferred construction so Qt picks the
 StatusNotifier backend rather than falling back to XEmbed). These need
 the tooling in Suggests (xvfb, stalonetray, xdotool, x11-utils, weston,
 qtwayland5, dbus, python3-dbus, python3-gi); any phase whose tooling is
 absent is skipped, not failed.
 .
 All commands require the 'sdwdate-gui' package, as the tests import its
 server module.

Package: privleap-tests
Architecture: all
Depends: ${misc:Depends},
 python3,
 privleap,
 sudo
Suggests: python3-coverage,
 python3-pytest,
 python3-hypothesis
Description: Security regression tests and fuzzers for the privleap privilege manager
 In-process security suite ('privleap-tests' command, no root): drives the
 REAL privleap code over exactly the surface an unprivileged local user can
 reach through their comm socket -- the place a bug could become arbitrary
 code execution as root.
 .
 The wire-protocol parser fuzzer wraps a server-side privleap session around a
 socketpair and feeds it a directed corpus plus random, structured, and
 mutational byte streams, asserting that every input is either parsed into a
 message type legal for that socket (with re-validated fields) or cleanly
 rejected -- never a crash, a hang (watchdog-guarded), or a type confusion --
 and that all valid traffic round-trips. The authorization-engine property
 test builds actions from the real account database and checks authorize_user
 against an independent reference model over thousands of randomized
 action/caller pairs, with the explicit invariant that a non-root caller is
 never authorized without a matching user or group rule, plus oracle-hardening
 (an unknown action and a forbidden one are indistinguishable). When
 python3-pytest and python3-hypothesis are present it also runs Hypothesis
 property tests of the pure parser helpers (argument-count codec round-trip,
 validate_id charset/length invariants).
 .
 Randomized fuzzer ('privleap-tests-fuzz' command, no root): the same parser
 fuzzer with a random seed and, when python3-coverage is present, a coverage
 report of the privleap library. The seed is printed so any finding is
 reproducible.
 .
 Coverage-guided fuzzer ('privleap-tests-fuzz-atheris' command, no root): an
 Atheris (libFuzzer) harness that drives the same server-side parser but
 mutates inputs guided by the coverage it observes inside the privleap library,
 reaching deep parser branches a blind generator rarely hits. It follows the
 ecosystem's fuzz_<pkg>.py convention and is ClusterFuzzLite-ready. Atheris is
 not packaged in Debian; install it with 'pip install atheris'. Without it the
 harness skips.
 .
 Stateful session fuzzer ('privleap-tests-session-fuzz' command, needs sudo):
 fuzzes the live daemon's multi-message session state machine and threading,
 not just single-frame parsing -- random and directed message sequences (out of
 order, split, interleaved) from many concurrent connections -- asserting the
 daemon never crashes or wedges and that an unauthorized action is never
 executed regardless of ordering. Runs a throwaway privleapd inside a private
 mount namespace, so the host's privleapd is untouched.
 .
 Live-daemon end-to-end test ('privleap-tests-e2e' command, needs sudo): runs
 the real privleapd and a real comm-socket client inside a private mount
 namespace (fresh tmpfs over /run and /etc/privleap, so the host's privleapd,
 state, and config are never touched and cleanup is automatic), proving end to
 end that an unauthorized action is never executed, an authorized one is, a
 malformed-frame barrage neither crashes nor corrupts the daemon's
 authorization, and an environment-injection attempt planted in the calling
 user's ~/.pam_environment and /etc/environment (LD_PRELOAD, BASH_ENV, marker
 variables) never reaches a root action.
 .
 Production-faithful variant ('privleap-tests-e2e-systemd' command, needs
 sudo): the same security phases against the REAL privleapd.service driven by
 systemd, so the daemon comes up exactly as in production (Type=notify
 handshake, watchdog, the genuine service environment and unit sandboxing) and
 actions run with the real systemd env. It mutates the live service (stop, swap
 config, start) and restores it on exit via atexit and signal handlers; the
 environment-injection check uses the real ~/.pam_environment and
 /etc/environment, backed up and restored.
 .
 The tests target the installed privleap by default; set PRIVLEAP_REPO to run
 them against a derivative-maker checkout instead.

Package: onion-grater-tests
Architecture: all
Depends: ${misc:Depends},
 python3,
 python3-yaml,
 python3-stem,
 python3-psutil,
 onion-grater
Suggests: tor,
 bitcoind
Description: Regression and reproduction tests for the onion-grater control-port filter
 In-process unit / reproduction suite ('onion-grater-tests' command): imports
 the real onion-grater filtering code and replays each application's Tor
 control command sequence, asserting legitimate commands are allowed and
 argument-injection variants are blocked. It also reproduces the fixed Bisq
 SETCONF deanonymization (a control-port argument-injection vulnerability) and
 the follow-up DEL_ONION / HSFETCH / onion_client_auth_add / AUTHCHALLENGE
 hardening, old-vs-new, through the same matcher. No root, no network, no real
 Tor; validated non-vacuous against the pre-fix tree.
 .
 Full-stack end-to-end ('onion-grater-tests-e2e' command): a throwaway offline
 tor plus the real onion-grater binary plus a control client over the veth
 network, proving the deanonymization vector reaches Tor on the old profile and
 is blocked (510) on the new one. Needs tor and sudo (only the privileged
 setup steps are sudo'd, and they are cleaned up).
 .
 Also under /usr/share/onion-grater-tests: a real-application driver
 (bitcoind_drive.py, which drives real bitcoind through the filter) and
 adversarial security probes (probe_bypass.py, probe_rewrite.py, verify_dos.py)
 that fuzz the filter for protocol bypasses and the partial-line busy-loop DoS.
 These need sudo and tor; see the README.
 .
 The tests target the installed onion-grater by default; set ONION_GRATER_REPO
 to run them against a derivative-maker checkout instead.

Package: genmkfile-tests
Architecture: all
Depends: ${misc:Depends},
 bash (>= 4),
 genmkfile,
 dctrl-tools,
 dpkg-dev,
 git,
 safe-rm
Description: Regression tests for the genmkfile build-helper target dispatch
 Drives the real genmkfile against a throwaway minimal Debian source package
 and asserts that the deb-cleanup and reprepro-remove / reprepro-add targets
 are routed through genmkfile's full variable setup (make_get_variables), not
 the cheap dependencies-only path reserved for deb-build-dep / deb-run-dep /
 deb-all-dep. This guards the fix for a dispatch mis-classification that
 aborted those targets with 'make_upstream_tarball_relative_path: unbound
 variable' (and the equivalent make_main_changes_file / make_package_list
 failures for the reprepro targets).
 .
 A second check covers the make_use_git_describe_for_version path: a repo
 that sets that flag but also ships debian/control (live-build) must still
 get its deb path variables set (deb-cleanup must not abort with an unbound
 variable) while keeping its git tag version from git describe (commit_<sha>),
 not the changelog version.
 .
 The 'genmkfile-tests' command needs no root, no network and no real reprepro
 (a stub wrapper stands in). It targets genmkfile from PATH by default; set
 GENMKFILE_BIN to test a specific genmkfile, or it falls back to a
 derivative-maker checkout under ~/derivative-maker.

Package: open-link-confirmation-tests
Architecture: all
Depends: ${misc:Depends},
 python3,
 python3-pyqt5,
 bash (>= 4),
 sed,
 grep,
 helper-scripts,
 open-link-confirmation
Description: Security and unit tests for the open-link-confirmation link/file dialog
 open-link-confirmation is the $BROWSER / x-www-browser handler: it receives a
 URL or file path from a potentially untrusted source and shows a confirmation
 dialog before opening it. The argument is displayed by piping it through
 helper-scripts' sanitize-string and rendering the result as HTML in a PyQt5
 QTextBrowser. The 'open-link-confirmation-tests' command exercises that whole
 pipeline. No root, no network, no real browser; Qt runs offscreen.
 .
 Sanitization contract: drives the real sanitize-string over a hostile battery
 (Unicode, RTL override, zero-width, ANSI/SGR, OSC-8 hyperlinks, C0/C1/DEL
 control bytes, oversized inputs, markup) and asserts the output stays
 display-safe (ASCII only, length-capped, no control or escape bytes other than
 newline and tab).
 .
 Qt rich-text differential: embeds the sanitized output in the script's exact
 HTML wrapper and parses it with the real Qt engine, asserting the argument
 introduces no clickable anchor or image. This encodes a known parser
 differential (a '<' followed by whitespace then a tag name survives
 sanitize-string's Python parser but Qt reconstructs the tag) as strict-xfail
 regression cases that flip to a hard failure once the bypass is fixed.
 .
 Static audit asserts every displayed message uses only the sanitized argument,
 never the raw argument; a bash unit test asserts source_config()'s
 env-over-config precedence. The tests target the installed
 open-link-confirmation and sanitize-string by default; set
 OPEN_LINK_CONFIRMATION_BIN and SANITIZE_STRING_BIN to test a checkout.
